Source Companion Blueprint: Picatrix / Ghāyat al-Ḥakīm
1. Source Identity

Author: Pseudo-Majrīṭī / disputed attribution.
Work: Ghāyat al-Ḥakīm, known in Latin as Picatrix.
Date: Arabic original likely 10th–11th century; translated into Latin in 1256 under Alfonso X of Castile.


Text type: Astrological-magical manual, philosophical occult encyclopedia, technical image-magic source.
Primary extraction mode: Extract structures of astral causality, talismanic theory, elections, materials, images, prayers, planetary correspondences, and metaphysical justifications.
Source status: Seminal medieval source for astral magic; major influence on later European occultism.


Copyright notes: Use public or archival texts where possible; avoid long quotation from modern translations. Prefer extensive structured summation.

2. Master Structural Reading

Picatrix is not contemplative Hermetic rebirth like the Corpus Hermeticum. It is a technical manual of astral image operations: how celestial forces are understood, selected, materialised, and ritually addressed.

Its progression is roughly:

define magic and cosmic hierarchy
explain celestial causality
catalogue planetary and zodiacal powers
instruct the making and timing of images
embed operations inside prayers, suffumigations, materials, and ritual speech
justify magic philosophically

The whole work asks: how does the celestial world become operative through image, timing, matter, and intention?

3. Part / Book Map
Book I — What Magic Is

Surface topic: Definition of magic, universe, heavens, human place.
Function: Establishes the metaphysical permission structure.
Main problems: Why magic is possible; how heaven affects earth; what the operator must know.
Key materials: cosmos, hierarchy, magic, wisdom, celestial causation.
Why first: Before operations, the reader needs a worldview.

Book II — Images, Elections, and Celestial Forms

Surface topic: Planetary/zodiacal images, elections, astrological configurations.
Function: Turns cosmology into technical procedure.
Main problems: Which forms receive which powers; how time qualifies matter.
Key materials: talismanic images, planets, zodiac, decans, elections.
Why second: It gives the grammar of astral image-making.

Book III — Planetary Rites and Materials

Surface topic: Prayers, suffumigations, colours, animals, stones, plants, planetary spirits.
Function: Shows the sensory-ritual ecology of astral magic.
Main problems: How planets are contacted through correspondences.
Key materials: incense, clothing, food, colours, names, invocations, planetary rites.
Why third: It thickens image-magic into full ritual environment.

Book IV — Philosophical and Ritual Synthesis

Surface topic: Spirit, intention, occult properties, final instructions.
Function: Explains how magical action fits into a larger philosophy of nature.
Main problems: What hidden powers are; how celestial and earthly powers interlock.
Key materials: occult virtues, spirit, nature, final operations.
Why last: It broadens the manual into occult philosophy.

