Source Companion Blueprint: The Greek Magical Papyri
1. Source Identity

Author: Various anonymous practitioners/scribes.
Work: Greek Magical Papyri, usually abbreviated PGM.
Edition / translation: Hans Dieter Betz, The Greek Magical Papyri in Translation is the standard English reference, but use short excerpts only; Preisendanz’s Greek/German edition is the older scholarly base.
Date: Materials mainly from Greco-Roman Egypt, roughly 2nd century BCE to 5th century CE.


Text type: Practical ritual corpus; spell collection; hymn collection; syncretic Greco-Egyptian magical manual.
Primary extraction mode: Extract procedures, ritual speech, divine names, materials, gestures, voces magicae, coercive/petitionary address, ritual aims, diagrams, and syncretic deity-forms.
Copyright notes: Use public-access excerpts cautiously. Prefer extensive summation and source locations over long quotation.

2. Master Structural Reading

The PGM is not a single authored book. It is a corpus of ritual technologies: fragments, handbooks, hymns, recipes, prayers, invocations, amulets, and operations gathered from Greco-Roman Egypt.

Its progression should not be forced into one linear argument. The companion should instead organise the corpus by ritual function:

approach to gods and daimons
spoken power and voces magicae
material operations
divination and revelation
protection, binding, healing, attraction, and practical aims
syncretic theology
operator identity and ritual authority

The key question is:

How does the PGM make speech, matter, name, image, and divine address operative?

3. Part / Corpus Map
Corpus Territory I — Divine Address

Surface topic: Hymns, prayers, invocations.
Function: Shows how the practitioner contacts divine powers.
Key materials: Helios, Hermes, Hekate, Isis, Osiris, Jewish divine names, Egyptian gods, Greek gods.
Why foundational: Without divine address, the spells become mere recipes.

Corpus Territory II — Magical Speech

Surface topic: voces magicae, barbarous names, palindromes, formulae.
Function: Explains language as force, not just meaning.
Key materials: nonsemantic syllables, secret names, repeated formulas, vowel sequences.
Why central: PGM’s strongest unique territory is operative utterance.

Corpus Territory III — Ritual Procedure

Surface topic: materials, timing, gestures, lamps, bowls, amulets, inks, plants.
Function: Turns speech into enacted operation.
Key materials: written charms, fumigations, offerings, diagrams, images, substances.

Corpus Territory IV — Divination and Revelation

Surface topic: dream sending, lamp divination, vessel divination, encounters with gods.
Function: Shows magic as a technology of receiving knowledge.

Corpus Territory V — Practical Operations

Surface topic: protection, healing, attraction, restraint, success, power, exorcistic aims.
Function: Shows the social/practical world in which the corpus operated.

Corpus Territory VI — Syncretic Theology

Surface topic: collapsing and combining deities.
Function: Explains the religious imagination of the PGM: Greek, Egyptian, Jewish, and other names interwoven.

