Source Companion Blueprint: Agrippa — Three Books of Occult Philosophy
1. Source Identity

Author: Heinrich Cornelius Agrippa von Nettesheim
Work: De occulta philosophia libri tres / Three Books of Occult Philosophy
Date: Full three-book Latin edition published 1533; English translation by John French published 1651.


Text type: Encyclopedic occult philosophy; Renaissance magical synthesis.
Primary extraction mode: Extract hierarchy, correspondences, natural virtues, celestial mechanics, numbers, names, angels, ritual theology, and the movement from nature → stars → divine/intellectual world.
Source status: Seminal public-domain occult source; public scans available on Internet Archive and Wikisource.


Copyright notes: Use public-domain editions for passage locations; modern translations should be summarized or quoted only briefly.

2. Master Structural Reading

Agrippa is the great architecture text of Western occultism. Unlike Picatrix, which is mainly astral operation, or the PGM, which is spell technology, Agrippa builds a total ladder of magical knowledge.

The work progresses through three worlds:

Book I — Natural magic: elemental world, hidden virtues, plants, stones, animals, mixtures, medicines, wonders of nature.
Book II — Celestial magic: stars, planets, numbers, harmonies, images, mathematics, music, geometry, astrology.
Book III — Intellectual / divine magic: religion, angels, divine names, Kabbalah, sacred language, prayer, ceremonial legitimacy.

Agrippa’s core claim is that magic is not one technique. It is the full philosophical science of how the worlds correspond.

3. Part / Book Map
Book I — Natural Magic

Function: Shows that matter is alive with hidden virtues.
Main problems: How earthly things carry occult powers; how plants, stones, animals, elements, and mixtures participate in cosmic life.
Why first: The magus begins with nature before ascending to heaven.

Book II — Celestial Magic

Function: Explains the mathematical and astral order that patterns nature.
Main problems: How planets, signs, numbers, proportions, music, images, and celestial figures structure power.
Why second: It reveals the sky as the ordering grammar behind natural effects.

Book III — Intellectual / Divine Magic

Function: Places magic under religion, angels, divine names, and sacred authority.
Main problems: How magic avoids becoming superstition or demonic misuse; how divine names, spirits, prayer, and Kabbalah complete the ascent.
Why last: Higher magic requires theology, purification, and divine sanction.

