Source Companion Blueprint: Aleister Crowley — Book 4 / Magick in Theory and Practice
1. Source Identity

Author: Aleister Crowley.
Primary work: Book 4, especially the combined structure later known through Magick: Liber ABA, Book 4.
Core components:

Part I: Mysticism
Part II: Magick
Part III: Magick in Theory and Practice
Part IV: Thelema: The Law / doctrinal Thelemic material

Text type: modern magical training manual; yogic discipline manual; ceremonial theory; Thelemic magical philosophy.

Primary extraction mode: extract method, practice, will, concentration, ritual tools, magical formulae, yoga, initiation, record-keeping, theory of magical action, and Thelemic self-authorisation.

Core identity: Crowley is not simply “Golden Dawn but edgier.” His unique territory is method + will + magical modernity: the conversion of inherited ritual magic into a practical discipline of training, experiment, self-transformation, and Thelemic authority.

2. Master Structural Reading

Crowley’s Book 4 is a training engine.

Where Agrippa maps the occult cosmos, Crowley asks:

What must the magician actually do, train, record, test, and become?

The movement is:

discipline the body
discipline attention
understand ritual implements
perform magical action
interpret magic through will
place the whole system under Thelema

Crowley’s key shift:

Magic is no longer primarily inherited correspondence, sacred tradition, or angelic reception. It becomes deliberate method: trained will acting through symbol, body, speech, ritual, and consciousness.

3. Part / Book Map
Part I — Mysticism

Function: establishes concentration, posture, breath, meditation, and yogic discipline.
Main problem: the untrained mind cannot perform magic.
Key materials: asana, pranayama, dharana, meditation, concentration, mystical attainment.
Why first: before ritual power, the operator must become capable of attention.

Part II — Magick

Function: explains ceremonial implements and magical equipment.
Main problem: how ritual tools externalise parts of the magical self.
Key materials: wand, cup, sword, pantacle, altar, scourge, dagger, oil, robe, bell, lamp.
Why second: the magician learns the symbolic body of practice.

Part III — Magick in Theory and Practice

Function: gives Crowley’s mature theory of magical action.
Main problem: what magic is, how intention operates, how rituals work, how formulae organise transformation.
Key materials: will, magical formulae, banishing, invocation, eucharist, consecration, divination, dramatic ritual, magical record.

Part IV — Thelema / The Law

Function: places practice under Thelemic revelation and doctrine.
Main problem: how magical method relates to True Will, the Aeon, and The Book of the Law.
Key materials: Thelema, True Will, Nuit, Hadit, Ra-Hoor-Khuit, law, initiation.

